@Vorawind First, "reducing global temperatures" is _not_ the goal. The goal is to reduce that part of the _rise_ in global temperatures that is caused by human activity. That is a very different thing.

Second, sure, there has been massive climate change in the far past. But that was usually over millennia, not in the space of 100 to 200 years like now. And there were no billions of people and human civilisation around. The earth, as a planet, will survive climate change. Life will survive climate change. But human civilisation will be affected dramatically, disrupting societies, economic systems, displacing people, destroying cultures and ways of life, and so on.

We should be doing this for selfish reasons - to retain or continue to raise our standard of living. Rapid climate change is threatening that, and we are responsible for a large part of it, so we should - theoretically - be able to influence that part.

