@alexgroot2508 Frankly, speaking as someone who lives in America, I think Europe should be concerned with their own homegrown theocrats. The American Religious Right is bad, it has damn near destroyed my country...but, for the time being, it appears to be in a kind of decline. They don't shape the Right's agenda and rhetoric like they used to. This is because Christianity's universalist message, even when filtered through RW politics, doesn't play well with immigration restriction. While it always played second fiddle to the interests of money, it now play third fiddle in the big scheme of the Right. It exists now as a kind of dog whistle for racial notions, much like the word "Christendom" in more distant times.

I think what held back an outright theocratic takeover was the actions of a fairly vigorous and active secularist movement(s) that arouse during the 70's and stretched on through to the last decade. We rightly mock today's "skeptics", but not long ago it was a noble title held by people worthy of it. While not completely successful, in the long term they did de-legitimize outright religious appeals. To say nothing of how secularism is explicitly enshrined in the Constitution. Slaveholders though they may have been, the Founders wisely understood the dangers of state sponsored religion. I know this also created fertile ground for fundamentalism to arise, a pox that has slowly spread across the Atlantic. Having a national church does, paradoxically, have a way of moderating religious fervor. However, just as constitutional secularism ultimately also stopped the Religious Right by holding their theocratic agenda against an ideal of secularism, so too does Europe's national churches make them vulnerable to a theocratic takeover.

That's because, over a very long period of time, maintaining national churches legitimizes the presence of religion in politics. The de facto secularism of Europe is the result of historical contingency, of faithful being battered by modernity and coming to terms with it. It's something, as an American, I don't fully understand. But I do understand this; de facto secularism is something with an expiration date. And while the fundamentalism is our fault, the fact remains is that now it's beginning to infect your population and you are all blindsided.

